Here is one possible implementation:

def lcs(seq1, seq2):
    m = len(seq1)
    n = len(seq2)
    table = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)] # Initialize the table with zeroes
    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            if seq1[i-1] == seq2[j-1]:
                table[i][j] = table[i-1][j-1] + 1
            else:
                table[i][j] = max(table[i-1][j], table[i][j-1])
    return table[-1][-1]
This function uses dynamic programming to calculate the length of the LCS. It creates a table of size (m+1)x(n+1), where m and n are the lengths of the two sequences. Each cell in this table represents the length of the LCS up to that point in the respective sequences. The algorithm iterates over all cells in the table, filling them according to whether the current characters in the sequences match or not. Finally, it returns the last element of the table, which corresponds to the length of the full LCS."}

